            <div type="edition" xml:lang="x-oldsun-Latn">
                <p>
         <lb n="1"/><g type="symbol" subtype="tennisball"/><g type="symbol" subtype="tennisball"/> vaṁ<unclear>ṅa</unclear> <unclear>p</unclear>un· I<unclear>n</unclear>i sakakala, pr<unclear>ə</unclear>bu ratu purane pun·, ḍivas·tu
         <lb n="2"/>ḍy<choice><sic>i</sic><corr>ǝ</corr></choice>, viṅaran· prəbu guru ḍe<unclear>va</unclear>ta p<choice><sic>ra</sic><corr>u</corr></choice>n· ḍivas·tu ḍyə ḍiṅaran· sri
         <lb n="3"/>baduga maharaja, ratu ha<unclear cert="low">j</unclear>i ḍi pakvan· pajajaran· sri sa<unclear>ṁ</unclear> ratu ḍe<lb 
	n="4" break="no"/>vata pun·</p> <p>ya nu ñusuk· na pakvan· ḍyə Anak· rahyi ḍeva nis·<lb 
	n="5" break="no"/>kala, sa siḍa mok·ta ḍi gunuṁ tiga, <choice><orig>qəcu</orig><reg>qəñ·cu</reg></choice><!-- Arlo: do you find this c clearer than that at the beginning of line 6? --> rahyiṁ <unclear>n</unclear>is·kala vas·tu
        <lb n="6"/><choice><orig>kaca:na</orig><reg>kañcana</reg></choice><!-- Arlo: actually the c seems quite clear to me; the length mark is of course unexpected, but it seems clear enough; I suppose we should here to normalize the c to ñc as in the case of qəñcu -->, saṁ siḍa mok·ta ka nusa laraṁ,</p> 
                <p>ya syi nu <unclear>ñ</unclear>yin· sakaka<lb 
	n="7" break="no"/>la, gugun<unclear>uṅ</unclear>an·, <unclear>ṅa</unclear>balay·,, ñyin· samiḍa, ñyin· saṁ hyi talaga <supplied reason="lost" evidence="paralel">va</supplied><lb 
	n="8" break="no"/>R̥na mahavijaya,</p> <p>ya s<supplied reason="lost">yi pun·</supplied>,,</p> <p><g type="symbol" subtype="tennisball"/><g type="symbol" subtype="tennisball"/> I saka, pañca pan·ḍa<lb 
	n="9" break="no"/>va ṅ<unclear>ə</unclear>ban· bumi <g type="symbol" subtype="tennisball"/><g type="symbol" subtype="tennisball"/>
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app loc="1">
                      	<lem>vaṁ<unclear cert="low">ṅa</unclear> <unclear>p</unclear>un·</lem>
		<rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">vaṁ na pun</rdg>
		<note>On the shape of <foreign>ṅa</foreign>, see <foreign>ṅabalay</foreign> in l. 7.</note><!-- Arlo: but in line 7, we also have <unclear>ṅa</unclear>balay·!!! -->
                    </app>
                    <app loc="2">
                  	<lem>ḍy<choice><sic>i</sic><corr>ǝ</corr></choice>, viṅaran·</lem>
		<rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">diya viṅaran</rdg>
		<note>A punctuation sign is clearly discernible between <foreign>ḍyi</foreign> and <foreign>viṅaran</foreign> on the estampage. Hasan Djafar suggests emending <foreign>viṅaran</foreign> to <foreign>diṅaran</foreign>.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="2">
                       	<lem>p<choice><sic>ra</sic><corr>u</corr></choice>n·</lem>
		<rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">prana</rdg>
		<note>Hasan Djafar's reading seems impossible to us, for there is unmistakably a sign between the <foreign>n</foreign> and the following <foreign>ḍi</foreign>, and this sign can only be a paten or punctuation. We feel compelled to emend because no word <foreign>pran</foreign> seems to exist in Sundanese or Javanese.<!-- Arlo: this argument only works against the reading pran· with paten; but  what about the possibility, explicitly mentioned in the preceding sentence, that that sign in question is a ","? --></note>

                    </app>
                    <app loc="2">
                                    <lem>ḍyə ḍiṅaran·</lem>
                                    <note>It would be possible to read <foreign>dyəṁ ḍiṅaran</foreign>.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="4">
                                    <lem>ñusuk· na</lem>
                                    <rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">ñusuk·na</rdg>
                                    <note>All predecessors have by their non-insertion of a space between <foreign>ñusuk</foreign> and <foreign>na</foreign> implied that <foreign>na</foreign> is a pronominal clitic, but it seems more convincing to take it as article <foreign xml:lang="x-oldsun-Latn">na</foreign> (<bibl><ptr target="Hardjadibrata2003_01"/><citedRange>547</citedRange></bibl>).<!-- Arlo: In general, I think we must assume readers share with us a basic understanding of Old Sundanese grammar and lexicon, so that a dictionary reference for such a frequently occurring word as na can be considered superfluous. If we do want to support our choice with a referencem is there not a page in N&T's book, that would be a more pertinent specifically to the interpretation of OS texts? --></note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="4">
                                    <lem>rahyi</lem>
                                    <rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">rahiyaṁ</rdg> 
                                    <note>We do not see the <foreign>anusvāra</foreign>/<foreign>cecak</foreign>.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="5">
                                    <lem>sa siḍa</lem>
                                    <rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">saṁ sida</rdg> 
                                    <note>Hasan Djafar explains that the <foreign>anusvāra</foreign>/<foreign>cecak</foreign> is present although hard to read. We are inclined to assume that it is absent. Cf. the cases of <foreign>sa ratu</foreign> and <foreign>rahyi</foreign> for <foreign>saṁ ratu</foreign> and <foreign>rahyiṁ</foreign> (= <foreign>rahiyaṁ</foreign>) above.</note><!-- Arlo: in all such cases, our edition(s) may want to make explicit how the words are to be normalized. See my comment just added to EG 6.1. -->
                    </app>
                    <app loc="5">
                                    <lem>mok·ta</lem>
                                    <rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">mok·ta</rdg>
                                    <note>We find a special <foreign>ka</foreign> with stroke underline that represents <foreign>paten</foreign>.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="5">
                                    <lem>gunuṁ</lem>
                                    <rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">guna</rdg>
                                    <note>There can be no doubt about our reading. See the toponym Gunuṅ Tiga in the <title>Fragment of Carita Parahyaṅan</title> (4b.4) as cited by Pleyte (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="Pleyte1911_01"/><citedRange>176</citedRange></bibl>): <foreign>gunuṅ tiga hulu alas utama jaṅkar</foreign>.<!-- Arlo: is there a reliable edition of CP that we could refer to in addition to the Pleyte reference? Or at least you can give a precise textual reference in the same way that you cite CP under  <app loc="6">--></note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="5">
                                    <lem><choice><orig>qəcu</orig><reg>qəñcu</reg></choice></lem><!-- case: add nasal ñ --><!-- Arlo: see my comment above. Let's await Dan's reponse to my comment in EG 6.1. -->
                                    <rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">I<supplied reason="omitted">ñ·</supplied>cu</rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="5">
                                    <lem><unclear>n</unclear>is·kala</lem>
                                    <rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">nis·kala</rdg>
                                    <note>The first consonant is very hard to read as <foreign>n</foreign>, but that is what is must be.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="6">
                                    <lem>nusa laraṁ</lem>
                                    <note>This place is mentioned in CP.21v: <foreign>Aya na səvə prəbu vaṁṅi ṅaran·na Iñana prəbu nis·kala vas·tu kañcana nu surup· di nusa §§ laraṁ</foreign> <quote>There is a king’s son, his name is fragrant, he is Prebu Niskala Wastu Kancana who deceased in the Nusa Larang</quote>.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="7">
                                    <lem><unclear>ṅa</unclear>balay·</lem>
                                    <note>The first consonant is unclear. If we are to follow Hasan Djafar who reads <foreign>ṅabalay</foreign>, then this means that at the beginning of line 1, we also need to read <foreign>ṅa</foreign>.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="7-8">
                                    <lem>talaga <supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previousedition">va</supplied>R̥na</lem>
                                    <note>Restoration proposed by Hasan Djafar. Cf. Pleyte <bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:Pleyte1911_01"/><citedRange>172</citedRange></bibl>, citation from FCP.6a: <foreign>ti saṁ hyiṁ talaga varna miñak· hanət· sagomboṁ Uyaḥ salave kəlek· lilitan· salave tək·tək· boEḥ putiḥ sakayuḥ hayam· sakurən·</foreign> <quote>From Talaga Warna: essential oil one <foreign>gombong</foreign>, salt 25 <foreign>kəlek</foreign>, waist cloth 25 <foreign>təktək</foreign>, white cloth one <foreign>kayuh</foreign>, chicken one <foreign>kurən</foreign></quote>.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>                
           
           <div type="translation" xml:lang="eng" resp="part:adgu part:argr">
                <p><foreign>Om pun</foreign>. This is the decree/message of his majesty the king of old, inaugurated here with the name Prabu Guru Dewata, <supplied reason="subaudible">and also</supplied> inaugurated here with the name Sri Baduga Maharaja, king of kings in Pakwan Pajajaran, Sri Sang Ratu Dewata, is inaugurated here.</p>  
                <p>He is the one who demarcates the Pakwan here, <supplied reason="subaudible">being</supplied> the child of Rahyang Dewa Niskala, he one who was released at Gunung Tiga; grandchild of Rahyang Niskala Wastu Kancana, the one who was released to Nusa Larang.</p><!-- Arlo: interesting that we have ... mokta di GT and ... mokta ka NL. Do you think it is significant?  -->
                <p>He, that one, produced the decree <seg cert="low">in the shape of a mountain</seg>, made hard the ground with stones; he produced fire-wood; he produced the holy Color Lake.</p> 
                <p>Victorious, was he! In the year: the five Pandawas carry the earth <supplied reason="subaudible">i.e. in 1<seg cert="low">2</seg>55 Śaka</supplied></p>
          </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <!--commentary encoded as per section §9.3 -->
         </div>
        <div type="bibliography">
           <p>The inscription was initially read by Friederich (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:Friederich1853_01"/><citedRange>442-468</citedRange></bibl>). Then Holle devoted a series of articles specifically to this inscription (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:Holle1869_01"/><citedRange>483-488</citedRange></bibl>, <bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:Holle1882_01"/><citedRange>90-98</citedRange></bibl>, <bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:Holle1882_02"/><citedRange>187-189</citedRange></bibl>). He was followed by Pleyte (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:Pleyte1911_01"/><citedRange>155-220</citedRange></bibl> and Poerbatjaraka (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:Poerbatjaraka1919-1921_01"/><citedRange>380-418</citedRange></bibl>), while the most recent study is that by Hasan Djafar (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:HasanDjafar2011_01"/><citedRange>1-13</citedRange></bibl>). Re-edited here by Aditia Gunawan &amp; Arlo Griffiths from the EFEO estampage. In our apparatus, variant readings are cited only from Hasan Djafar's edition.</p>
               
